**CONDITIONAL STATEMENTS**
Enables a program to make decisions based on inputs
** Types of conditional statements**
-> if else ->
->if ,else if,else
->conditional expretions-->ternary operator

general syntax:
{}-->represents a block of code
scenario one--** one condition to be met** eg checking whether a number is even or not
if (condition){
    //what happens if condition is met

}else{
    //what happens when the condition is false
}

scenario two--** multiple conditions**eg checking students grades
if (condition 1){
    //what happens if condition 1 is true
}
else if (condition 2){
    //what happens if condition 2 is true
}
else if( condition 3){
    //what happens if condition 3 is true
}else{
    //what happens when all conditions are false
}
        in class task
1. write a js program that checks if a number is even or odd
2. write a js programm that displays the largest interger among three intergers
--> for each of the tasks take user input        

**Ternary operator**
-> ?
-> it is the shorthand of if else statements
->it works with only one condtion
-> the syntax
        condition ? what happens if true: what happens if false
             task
q. using ternary operator check if a person is eligible to vote.--> anyone voting has to be 18 years and older





**JS DATA STRUCTURES**
we use d/ss to store multiple values in variables
1. Arrays
2. Objects
         **JS ARRAYS**
A data structure used to hold multiple values in an ordered manner
represented using []
->equvalent of lists in python  
**properties**
1.they are ordered--indexing
  n/b no negative indexing in js arrays
2.mutable--values can be changed
3.can contain multiple values of any type 
        **array operation**
1.creating an array   
2.accessing values in an array-use indexing and its zero based  
3.updating values in an array
--->we can use index 
4.determining number of values in an array-->we use the length feature
5.adding items to an array
  a).add at the end--> we use .push()
  b).add at the beginning--we use .unshift()
6.removing items from an array
a).remove the first item-->we use shift()
b).remove the last item-->we use pop 

           **OBJECTS***
Object are data strucures that store data in key-value pairs
-> they are the equivalent of python dictionaries
     **properties of objects**
1. store data in key-value pairs
2. they use keys to access values
3. keys are unique
4. keys have to e strings
5. values can be of any data type
->objects are represented using {}
**properties**->this is the cmbination of keys and values  
properties are comma separated              
property=key + value

**object operations**
1. creating an object
2. accessing values in an object
     a).Dot notation
     ->use the dot operator followed by the key
     ->can only be used with keys that follow identifier(variables) naming rules
     ->dot notaton cant work for keys with spaces
     b).bracket notaion
     ->uses square brackets taking keys as strings ["key]
     ->can accept keys with spaces



